          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "3. Error Handling and Rate Limits"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The API returns standard HTTP status codes (e.g., 429 for rate limits, 500 for server errors). Implement exponential backoff for retries and log errors with correlation IDs for debugging. Rate limits are typically 1000 requests per minute per API key; monitor usage via headers like "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "X-RateLimit-Remaining",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "4. Deployment and Security Best Practices"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Deploy the API behind a gateway for load balancing and security. Use environment variables for API keys, enforce HTTPS, and validate input to prevent injection attacks. Regularly update SDKs and monitor API health with tools like Prometheus for metrics collection."
          }
